note top of ApplicantsManager
  **FLAW 1: God Object (SRP Violation)**
  5,769 lines handling: table rendering,
  modal management, status updates,
  prerequisites, ratings, exports,
  English proficiency, scholarships,
  search/filter, and document management.
  Should be split into 5+ focused classes.
end note

note right of auth_api
  **FLAW 2: Bypasses Model Layer**
  11 of 14 routes execute raw SQL
  via get_db_connection() instead
  of delegating to models/users.py.
  models/users.py has create_user()
  but auth_api duplicates it twice:
  /create-user AND /register do the
  same thing.

  **FLAW 3: Duplicate Endpoints**
  POST /create-user ≈ POST /register
  POST /edit-user overlaps PUT /user/{id}
end note

note bottom of test_scores_api
  **FLAW 4: Bypasses Model Layer**
  Duolingo endpoint uses db_transaction()
  directly instead of a model function.
  Other test scores use models/test_scores.
end note

note left of statuses_bp
  **FLAW 5: Inconsistent Model Usage**
  reorder_statuses_route() does direct SQL
  UPDATE via get_db_connection() while all
  other routes delegate to models/statuses.
end note

note bottom of application_info
  **FLAW 7: Soft String Reference**
  application_info.sent stores a status
  name string that references
  status_configuration.status_name
  by value, with no FK constraint.
  Renaming a status requires UPDATE
  of application_info in the same txn.
end note

note bottom of db_util
  **FLAW 6: Inconsistent DB Access**
  Two competing patterns:
  ① get_db_connection() — manual try/except
  ② db_helpers.db_connection/db_transaction
  ····— context manager (newer, cleaner)
  Only models/documents uses db_helpers.
  Everything else uses raw get_db_connection().
end note

